<br>
Heck, no.  Most reasonable folks admit that France has been a useful counterweight to the US in the past.  And Tony Blair has definitely influenced US policy on several issues.  Personally, I wish Europe had been successful in reigning in, for example, Bush's ridiculous steel tariffs.<br>
<br>
The entire US government system is one of checks and balances.  We understand the need for them.  But there's a difference between a 'check' and a foe.<br>
<br>
The problem with the Iraq situation is that France changed the subject.  For them, it's not about containing Iraq.  It never was.  It's about containing the US, at *any* cost.  They've sacrificed the UN Security Council to keep Hussein in power.  They would have damaged NATO, too -- except that they left in 1966 (militarily), in a previous attempt to check US power.<br>
<br>
To have a former ally place &quot;Containing the US&quot; as its #1 foreign policy goal feels like a betrayal.  Heck, I'd bet a toe that the Pentagon is now making contingency plans for what they do if the French sail their leaky aircraft carrier to the Persian Gulf, and I do not mean as an ally.<br>
